{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17596337","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17596337"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:12:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:12:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15404"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15404"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.85,0.08,0,0,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8095"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69823"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8095","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8095"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15404"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55279"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"266"},{"type":"tags","id":"1126"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"6942"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19639"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19642"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69823","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69823"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe dentate (pectinate) line is an important anatomical landmark in the anal canal that divides the upper and lower regions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following correctly describes the characteristics of internal and external haemorrhoids?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Internal = above dentate line, covered by mucosa; external = below dentate line, covered by skin","Internal = below dentate line, covered by skin; external = above dentate line, covered by mucosa","Internal = below dentate line with severe pain; external = above dentate line without pain","Internal = covered by skin with thrombosis; external = covered by mucosa without thrombosis","Internal = painful with dark bleeding; external = painless with bright red bleeding"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe key distinguishing features of haemorrhoids are based on their location relative to the dentate line and their symptoms:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInternal haemorrhoids occur above the dentate line and are covered by mucosa, while external haemorrhoids occur below the dentate line and are covered by skin\u003C/strong\u003E. This is the correct answer.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInternal haemorrhoids below the dentate line with external above\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - this is the reverse of the correct anatomy.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInternal haemorrhoids being painful and external being painless\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - internal haemorrhoids are typically painless due to visceral innervation, while external haemorrhoids are painful due to somatic innervation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInternal haemorrhoids being covered by skin and external by mucosa\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - this is the reverse of the correct tissue coverage.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInternal haemorrhoids being painful with dark bleeding\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - internal haemorrhoids typically cause painless bright red bleeding, while external haemorrhoids present as painful masses.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInternal haemorrhoids can be graded I-IV based on their degree of prolapse, while external haemorrhoids may become thrombosed causing severe pain.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Internal haemorrhoids occur above the dentate line and are covered by mucosa, while external haemorrhoids occur below the dentate line and are covered by skin","Internal haemorrhoids typically present with painless bright red bleeding, while external haemorrhoids present as painful perianal masses","Internal haemorrhoids can be graded I-IV based on prolapse severity"],"references":["Mott T, Latimer K, Edwards C. Hemorrhoids: Diagnosis and Treatment Options. Am Fam Physician. 2018 Feb 1;97(3):172-179. PMID: 29431977","Sun Z, Migaly J. Review of Hemorrhoid Disease: Presentation and Management. Clin Colon Rectal Surg. 2016 Mar;29(1):22-9. doi: 10.1055/s-0035-1568144. PMID: 26929748; PMCID: PMC4755769","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55279"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15404"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55279","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55279"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-12T20:01:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-12T20:04:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8095"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69823"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"